  "prompt": "Differentiate a^x up to 4 terms?",
  "response": "To differentiate the function \\(a^x\\) with respect to \\(x\\), we first use the logarithmic differentiation technique. Here's how you can do it:\n\n1. Begin with the function:\n   \\[\n   y = a^x\n   \\]\n   where \\(a\\) is a constant.\n\n2. Take the natural logarithm of both sides:\n   \\[\n   \\ln y = \\ln(a^x) = x \\ln a\n   \\]\n\n3. Differentiate both sides with respect to \\(x\\):\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d}{dx}(\\ln y) = \\frac{d}{dx}(x \\ln a)\n   \\]\n\n   Using the chain rule on the left and the constant rule on the right:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{1}{y} \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\ln a\n   \\]\n\n4. Solve for \\(\\frac{dy}{dx}\\):\n   \\[\n   \\frac{dy}{dx} = y \\ln a\n   \\]\n\n5. Substitute back for \\(y = a^x\\):\n   \\[\n   \\frac{dy}{dx} = a^x \\ln a\n   \\]\n\nThe derivative of \\(a^x\\) is \\(a^x \\ln a\\).\n\nIf you're looking for the expansion of the derivative function up to 4 terms, the expression \\(a^x\\) itself can be expanded using its Taylor series around \\(x = 0\\), but the derivative function does not traditionally have \"terms\" unless further specified for particular conditions or transformations (like logarithmic expansions). However, if the task involves applying the derivative multiple times, this would involve higher-order derivatives, typically considered in Taylor series or other forms of expansion. Please clarify if further transformation or expansion is required.",
